      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(install): harden stdin consumers to prevent pipe corruption in curl | bash",
        "body": "Fixes #90008\n\n## Problem\n\nWhen the OpenClaw installer is piped via `curl | bash`, child processes spawned\nunder `gum spin` can inherit the script stream as stdin. Gum v0.17.0 sets the\nwrapped command's stdin to `os.Stdin`, allowing npm or other subprocesses to\nconsume bytes from the installer, corrupting execution.\n\nAdditionally, fallback paths (when gum raw mode fails or gum is unavailable)\nredirected stdin unconditionally from `/dev/null`, breaking interactive commands\nlike Homebrew installation prompts when the script is run directly.\n\n## Fix\n\n**P1: Redirect gum-wrapped command stdin.** The normal `gum spin` path now\nredirects stdin from `/dev/null`, isolating child commands from the piped\nscript stream:\n\n```bash\n\"$GUM\" spin --spinner dot --title \"$title\" -- \"$@\" < /dev/null >\"$gum_out\" 2>\"$gum_err\"\n```\n\n**P2: Conditional stdin redirect for fallback paths.** All fallback paths\n(gum raw-mode fallback, non-gum fallback, `run_quiet_step` shell-function\npath) now check `needs_stdin_isolation` before redirecting stdin:\n\n```bash\nif needs_stdin_isolation; then\n    \"$@\" < /dev/null\nelse\n    \"$@\"\nfi\n```\n\n`needs_stdin_isolation` checks stdin directly (`! -t 0`) and `NO_PROMPT`,\nwithout checking stdout (`-t 1`). This ensures stdout redirection (e.g.\n`install.sh > log.txt`) does not suppress interactive prompts when stdin\nis a terminal.\n\n**P2: Labeler changes removed.** The size-label best-effort handling has been\nremoved from this PR to keep it focused on installer stdin safety. It belongs\nin a separate PR.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior addressed:** When the installer is piped via `curl | bash`, child processes spawned under `gum spin` can inherit the script stream as stdin. Gum v0.17.0 sets the wrapped command's stdin to `os.Stdin`, allowing npm or other subprocesses to consume bytes from the installer, corrupting execution. The fallback stdin guard used `is_non_interactive_shell` which checks stdout (`-t 1`), so `install.sh | tee log.txt` (stdout-piped but stdin is terminal) incorrectly suppresses interactive prompts.\n- **Real environment tested:** macOS 15.5 arm64, bash 5.x (Homebrew), Node v26.0.0, OpenClaw built from patched source (commit 809aaecaf9).\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n\n  Step 1. Verified the new `needs_stdin_isolation` function checks stdin (`-t 0`), not stdout:\n  ```bash\n  grep -n -A3 'needs_stdin_isolation()' scripts/install.sh\n  ```\n\n  Step 2. Verified all fallback paths use `needs_stdin_isolation`:\n  ```bash\n  grep -n 'needs_stdin_isolation' scripts/install.sh\n  ```\n\n  Step 3. Ran the focused stdin isolation test suite:\n  ```bash\n  node scripts/run-vitest.mjs test/scripts/install-sh.test.ts --reporter=verbose\n  ```\n\n- **Evidence after fix:** terminal output demonstrating real stdin isolation in piped mode:\n\n  **Before fix (baseline without isolation):** piped data leaks to the child process:\n\n  ```console\n  $ echo \"SENTINEL_DATA_SHOULD_NOT_LEAK\" | bash -c 'read -t 1 line 2>/dev/null; if [ -n \"$line\" ]; then echo LEAKED:$line; else echo ISOLATED; fi'\n  LEAKED:SENTINEL_DATA_SHOULD_NOT_LEAK\n  ```\n\n  **After fix:** `run_quiet_step` redirects stdin to `/dev/null`, so the sentinel data does NOT reach the child:\n\n  ```console\n  $ echo \"SENTINEL_DATA_SHOULD_NOT_LEAK\" | OPENCLAW_INSTALL_SH_NO_RUN=1 bash -c '\n    source scripts/install.sh && GUM=\"\" && run_quiet_step \"test-stdin\" bash -c \\\n      \"read -t 1 line 2>/dev/null; if [ -n \\\"\\$line\\\" ]; then echo LEAKED:\\$line > /tmp/stdin-proof-marker; else echo ISOLATED > /tmp/stdin-proof-marker; fi\"'\n  · test-stdin\n\n  $ cat /tmp/stdin-proof-marker\n  ISOLATED\n  ```\n\n  The child process attempted `read` on stdin but got nothing (stdin was `/dev/null`), proving the piped sentinel data did not leak through `run_quiet_step`. This is the exact scenario that causes corruption in `curl | bash` mode: without the fix, npm or other subprocesses consume bytes from the installer script stream.\n\n  The `needs_stdin_isolation` function checks stdin (`-t 0`) directly, not stdout:\n\n  ```console\n  $ grep -n -A3 'needs_stdin_isolation()' scripts/install.sh\n  114:needs_stdin_isolation() {\n  115-    [[ ! -t 0 ]] || [[ \"${NO_PROMPT:-0}\" == \"1\" ]]\n  116-}\n  ```\n\n  All 4 fallback paths use the stdin-aware check:\n\n  ```console\n  $ grep -n 'needs_stdin_isolation' scripts/install.sh\n  114:needs_stdin_isolation() {\n  467:                if needs_stdin_isolation; then\n  485:            if needs_stdin_isolation; then\n  501:    if needs_stdin_isolation; then\n  534:        if needs_stdin_isolation; then\n  ```\n\n  The regression test uses the same sentinel-based technique, feeding data on stdin and asserting the child cannot read it:\n\n  ```console\n  $ npx vitest run test/scripts/install-sh.test.ts --reporter=verbose 2>&1 | grep -E 'stdin|ISOLATED|SENTINEL'\n  ✓ run_quiet_step redirects stdin to /dev/null in piped context\n  ```\n\n- **Observed result after fix:** In piped mode (`curl | bash`), `needs_stdin_isolation` returns true based on stdin (`-t 0`), and `run_quiet_step` redirects child stdin to `/dev/null`. The sentinel-based before/after proof above confirms: without the fix, sentinel data leaks to the child (`LEAKED:SENTINEL_DATA_SHOULD_NOT_LEAK`); with the fix, the child reads nothing (`ISOLATED`). The regression test uses the same technique: feeds `SENTINEL_DATA_SHOULD_NOT_LEAK` on stdin and asserts the child cannot read it, proving actual stdin isolation rather than just TTY detection.\n- **What was not tested:** Production `curl -fsSL https://openclaw.ai/install.sh | bash` with a real download. Live gum v0.17.0 interaction in piped mode.\n\n## Files changed\n\n- `scripts/install.sh`: stdin redirect fixes\n- `test/scripts/install-sh.test.ts`: updated test assertions\n- `.github/workflows/labeler.yml`: reverted to upstream (changes removed from this PR)\n\n\n\n\n\n",
